      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What five factors move a Brisbane property valuation most?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The five factors that most consistently move a Brisbane property valuation are: land size and configuration (wide, usable land commands the greatest premium), position and street character (ridge streets, river views, and park frontage add measurable value), renovation quality and condition (only complete, well-executed renovations achieve a genuine premium), school catchment access (sought-after primary and secondary catchments drive consistent price premiums across the inner east), and aspect and natural light (north-facing rear yards attract buyers and show up clearly in comparable sales data)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What can sellers do to support a higher bank valuation before listing?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Present the property well at the valuation inspection: clean, maintained, and free of obvious deferred work. Have documentation ready for any significant renovation or improvement, including council approvals and builder invoices. If recent comparable sales support a higher value, share them with your agent before the valuation so they can communicate that context appropriately. And if you are preparing to sell, a strong open market campaign with competitive bidding is the strongest evidence of value a bank valuer can use."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why does a bank valuation come in lower than an agent appraisal in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Bank valuers are instructed to be conservative because the lender is securing a loan against the asset. They weight confirmed historical sales over current market sentiment and must document their methodology in a way that is defensible and repeatable. An agent appraisal can incorporate the emotional premium from buyer competition and presentation, and a skilled agent with a deep buyer database may achieve prices above what recent comparable sales alone would suggest. The gap is structural, not a sign that either number is inaccurate."
      }
    }
  ]
}
